@Dyson Lewis

Correct. Next to the native 120Hz and native 90Hz modes, they have an additional mode that allows the software to be rendered at 60 fps. They use a motion interpolation technique to boost the in-game frame rate of 60 fps to 120 fps in order to reduce frame latency and the resulting motion sickness.

Combine this with black frame insertion and you have a consistently clear image with next to no motion artefacts. This is made possible with the instant response ability that is unique to self emissive display technology. You won't achieve this sort of motion accuracy on any other display technology.Ôªø

@Manne Powrd

Correct. And the display driver inside the iPhone X is a Samsung model as well, which means that iPhone's changes on Samsung's OLED displays are limited to software only.

This also means that iPhone is restricted to selection of OLED displays that Samsung offers to third-parties. iPhone could have gone for a VR version of their display though, but they most likely opted for greater availability instead.Ôªø
